132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 758
S.P. 291 In Senate, February 25, 2025
Resolve, to Update Flood Mapping in the Sandy River Watershed to
Federal Emergency Management Agency Standards
Reference to the Committee on Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry suggested and
ordered printed.
DAREK M. GRANT
Secretary of the Senate
Presented by Senator BLACK of Franklin.
Cosponsored by Representative HALL of Wilton and
Senators: MARTIN of Oxford, TEPLER of Sagadahoc, Representatives: BRIDGEO of
Augusta, BUNKER of Farmington, CARUSO of Caratunk, FROST of Belgrade, POIRIER of
Skowhegan, ROLLINS of Augusta.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Sec. 1. Maine Office of Community Affairs; Sandy River watershed flood
2 mapping update. Resolved: That, in coordination with the United States Department
3 of Homeland Security, Federal Emergency Management Agency; the Department of
4 Transportation; the Department of Environmental Protection; the Department of Inland
5 Fisheries and Wildlife; the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry; Maine
6 Geological Survey; the Department of Defense, Veterans and Emergency Management,
7 Maine Emergency Management Agency and other relevant state agencies, the Maine
8 Office of Community Affairs shall develop and implement a pilot project to update flood
9 modeling and flood mapping within the Sandy River watershed. The office may enter into
10 an agreement with the United States Department of Interior, United States Geological
11 Survey, other federal agencies or a consultant to support development and implementation
12 of the pilot project. The office shall provide technical assistance and coordination to
13 communities within the watershed and to other groups involved in the pilot project,
14 including, but not limited to, regional councils, community and environmental
15 organizations and riverfront landowners. The office shall request or otherwise acquire
16 federal or other nonstate funding to support the costs of developing and implementing the
17 pilot project.
18 SUMMARY
1199 This resolve directs the Maine Office of Community Affairs to develop and implement
2200 a pilot project to update flood modeling and flood mapping within the Sandy River
2211 watershed. The office is required to request or otherwise acquire federal or other nonstate
2222 funding to support the costs of developing and implementing the pilot project.
